<h1>1. Executive Summary</h1>
<p>The Learner Modeling Engine (LME) is an intelligent, real-time educational platform that solves the issue of "invisible struggle" in digital learning. By accurately inferring a student's cognitive state from telemetry—such as idle time, attempt counts, and mastery score—it provides targeted, context-aware interventions before a student becomes disengaged or frustrated.</p>
<p>LME caters to two distinct roles: students and instructors. Students interact with module quizzes (Mathematics or Logic Patterns), receiving dynamic AI-generated hints adapted to their "Zone of Proximal Development". Instructors access a live dashboard offering real-time situational awareness (a panopticon of learner states), enabling them to monitor the entire class's engagement status and forcibly invoke AI hints on behalf of struggling students.</p>
<p>Unlike a conventional quiz application that limits metrics to correct/incorrect answers upon submission, LME continuously evaluates a "Struggle Index" over a WebSocket heartbeat. Furthermore, instead of static hints, it provides dynamic, multi-turn AI scaffolding leveraging Productive Failure theories, ensuring hints match behavioral escalation without revealing answers directly.</p>
<p>The engine consists of three main components: an adaptive interactive quiz engine, an Intelligent Tutoring System (ITS) utilizing generative AI, and a high-availability Live Instructor Dashboard for live monitoring.</p>
<p>The technical stack fundamentally relies on a React/Vite single-page application frontend, a FastAPI WebSocket backend handling state management and broadcasts, backed by SQLite for relational persistence.</p>

<h1>2. System Architecture</h1>
<h2>2.1 Overall architecture</h2>
<p>LME follows a robust 3-tier architecture designed to maintain persistent states for live telemetry streams:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Frontend (React/Vite) — port 3000:</strong> Handles user interfaces, rendering quiz state, tracking DOM interactions to measure idle time, and emitting WebSocket telemetry.</li>
    <li><strong>Backend (FastAPI) — port 8000:</strong> Acts as the central router for stateless requests (auth, hints) and stateful interactions (WebSockets). Implements the behavioral classification and debounce logic.</li>
    <li><strong>Database (SQLite via SQLAlchemy):</strong> Local persistence engine storing users, encrypted passwords, and telemetry logs.</li>
</ul>
<p>Communication bridging the frontend and backend consists of:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>REST (HTTP):</strong> Used for stateless operations such as POST /login, POST /register, POST /hint, and POST /intervention.</li>
    <li><strong>WebSocket (ws://):</strong> Used for the foundational real-time telemetry heartbeat carrying interaction metrics, state broadcast to students, and Live Feed syncs for the Instructor module.</li>
</ul>

<h2>2.2 Full tech stack table</h2>
<table>
    <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Technology</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Frontend</td><td>React (18), Vite, react-router-dom</td><td>UI rendering, routing, custom styling</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Backend</td><td>FastAPI, uvicorn, WebSockets</td><td>Async API, robust broadcast socket management</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Database</td><td>SQLite, SQLAlchemy</td><td>Relational persistence of users and telemetry</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Auth</td><td>passlib (bcrypt), python-jose</td><td>Stateless role-based authentication and secure encryptions</td></tr>
    <tr><td>ML (Historical)</td><td>scikit-learn, SHAP</td><td>Historical OULAD-driven behavior clustering (not used at runtime)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>AI</td><td>OpenAI API (GPT-4o-mini)</td><td>Generating escalated contextual ITS scaffolding hints</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Data Source</td><td>OULAD Dataset</td><td>Reference dataset historically parsed for ML feature engineering</td></tr>
</table>

