<h2>2.4 Data flow diagram</h2>
<p>The complete lifecycle executes in near real-time across the infrastructure. Initially, the Student opens their browser and navigates to the login screen, authenticating via a REST POST which verifies SQLite and issues a JWT context. The React application opens the Student Quiz component, which immediately attempts a WebSocket connection (ws://).</p>
<p>The backend performs a JWT handshake on the first packet, validating the identity and broadcasting a "In Lobby" presence message to all instructors. As the student answers questions, the custom interval_update fires every 5 seconds (heartbeat) pushing accumulated attempt_count, actual idle_time, and mastery indexes.</p>
<p>The backend WebSocket connection computes the Struggle Index and checks thresholds (e.g., attempt_count &gt;= 3). Upon classification changes—such as shifting into "Struggling"—it triggers a message fallback string. The backend relays this state format back to the student (popping a FeedbackToast) and concurrently syncs the dashboard_update broadcast packet to the instructor. Finally, it commits the state array row asynchronously down to SQLite telemetry_logs.</p>

<h1>3. Authentication System</h1>
<h2>3.1 Registration and login</h2>
<p>The API endpoint POST /auth/register accepts a JSON payload of: email, password, name, and role. It verifies email uniqueness and hashes the password via bcrypt (passlib) before inserting it as a User class into the SQLite database.</p>
<p>The API endpoint POST /auth/login accepts email and password. Following hash verification, it responds with: access_token, token_type: "bearer".</p>
<p>The JWT Token Payload encodes the following structure:</p>
<ul>
    <li>sub: contains the user email (string)</li>
    <li>name: contains the user's explicit real name (string)</li>
    <li>role: contains "student" or "instructor"</li>
    <li>id: contains the backend integer primary key (id)</li>
    <li>exp: Expiry is set 24 hours from issuance</li>
</ul>

<h2>3.2 Role system</h2>
<p>The auth logic operates two rigidly enforced roles defining application rendering: "student" and "instructor".</p>
<p>On the frontend, AuthContext handles the redirection tree post-login. Students are inherently navigated straight onto "/quiz" forcing telemetry loading. Instructors are guided onto "/dashboard" where they join the teacher observer pool. Furthermore, individual paths are blocked tightly by ProtectedRoute which evicts mismatched user tokens entirely.</p>

<h2>3.3 WebSocket authentication handshake</h2>
<p>FastAPI WebSocket connections strictly deny unauthenticated payloads. The procedural lifecycle includes:</p>
<ul>
    <li>Step 1: The React Hook connects natively to ws://localhost:8000/ws/{client_id}.</li>
    <li>Step 2: Client transmits an initial authentication packet: {"type": "authenticate", "token": "&lt;JWT&gt;"}.</li>
    <li>Step 3: Server synchronously decodes the token against the HS256 secret to fetch the user name variable.</li>
    <li>Step 4: If invalid or completely omitted, FastAPI forcefully closes the pipeline (Close Code 1008).</li>
    <li>Step 5: If valid, the backend updates the cache and announces standard presence packets (Engaged in Lobby).</li>
</ul>
<p>Instructor endpoints route automatically based on client_id="instructor" following an almost identical JWT decode gate. Post-validation, the ConnectionManager appends the instructor to the broadcast roster and immediately dumps the entire latest_student_states cache back to them as a bootstrap sync mechanism.</p>

<h1>4. The Quiz Engine</h1>
<h2>4.1 Module selection</h2>
<p>Upon launching the system, students face a gatekeeper UI listing two explicitly configured modules: Mathematics and Logic Patterns. Selecting a module sets the selectedModule context parameter, resets scores to zero, and instantly emits an interval_update via socket marking the exact current_question_text allowing the Instructor dashboard to reflect that the user actively departed the "In Lobby" screen.</p>

<h2>4.2 Question structure</h2>
<p>The frontend defines question schema inside data/quizQuestions.js using JSON:</p>
<div class="code">{ id, question, options[], correct, difficulty, module }</div>
<p>The Mathematics module comprises exactly 10 questions. Difficulty map: 3 Easy, 5 Medium, 2 Hard.</p>
<p>The Logic Patterns module comprises exactly 10 questions. Difficulty map: 5 Easy, 3 Medium, 2 Hard.</p>

<h2>4.3 Quiz navigation</h2>
<p>Navigation features include:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Previous button:</strong> Disabled on question 1. Allows jumping to the prior question while wiping local tracking attempt timers, and emitting an interval telemetry notification backwards.</li>
    <li><strong>Skip question button:</strong> Advances forward wrapping across the remaining length to the next unanswered question. Ensures skipped puzzles are not mandated to finish the whole index. Emits instantaneous state changes.</li>
    <li><strong>Done button:</strong> Visible strictly on the very final question in place of 'skip'. Emits type='session_complete' overriding telemetry.</li>
    <li><strong>Lobby button:</strong> Allows the student to completely wipe the active quiz array mapping to clean 0s. Fires an interval_update signaling the instructor that the learner is back to 'Selecting...'.</li>
    <li><strong>Progress dots:</strong> Dynamically shaded components displaying logic checks (correct/answered vs current viewing vs pending unengaged).</li>
    <li><strong>Progress bar:</strong> Fills horizontally evaluating (answeredSet.size / questions.length) explicitly counting valid finished responses, NOT the student's active array index.</li>
</ul>

<h2>4.4 Session completion logic</h2>
<p>Quiz flow termination triggers if:</p>
<ul>
    <li>1. The student clicks 'Done' directly situated on the last question of the index pool.</li>
    <li>2. The student submits a valid 'correct' response resolving the last numerical question natively.</li>
    <li>3. The student submits a valid 'correct' response and no subsequent unanswered variables exist ahead of them internally.</li>
</ul>
<p>Upon termination, isFinished is tripped to True, clearing heartbeats. It fires one final session_complete packet containing total_hints and cumulative mistake records, keeping the socket completely alive statically while unblocking a final Session Summary dashboard.</p>

<h2>4.5 Answer submission logic</h2>
<p>The mechanical pipeline mapping click resolution works explicitly:</p>
<ul>
    <li>1. Validating visual response matching option directly to strings in object config.</li>
    <li>2. Visual Feedback animation fires. Correct entries generate a green 600ms 'pop' delay. Wrong answers queue an 850ms red CSS jitter animation.</li>
    <li>3. Failed selection explicitly inflates the immediate underlying attempt_count parameter.</li>
    <li>4. A submit_answer socket JSON overrides internal delays processing is_correct variables immediately out to the backend manager.</li>
    <li>5. If it was correct, it logs directly onto the AnsweredSet tracker Set and automatically triggers jump logics to move the currentIdx frame.</li>
</ul>

<h1>5. Telemetry System</h1>
<h2>5.1 Telemetry packet structure</h2>
<p>The React app invokes a rigorous JSON payload dictionary defining actual real-time state configurations wrapped locally via buildTelemetryPacket:</p>
<div class="code">student_id: string (JWT value)
student_name: string (JWT value)
module: string (maths or logic)
current_question_text: string
idle_time: number (seconds)
attempt_count: number
is_correct: boolean
current_score: number (Mastery Decimal 0.0 - 1.0)
totalMistakes: number
totalIdleTime: number
answeredCount: number
totalHintsRequested: number
type: string (interval_update | submit_answer | session_complete | hint_received | state_change | request_hint)
history: array (list of {question, attempts})</div>

<h2>5.2 Heartbeat mechanism</h2>
<p>The fundamental connection runs a massive continuous stream processing via setInterval set at strictly 5000ms. Handled entirely via component mount within StudentQuiz using an empty dependency block.</p>
<p>Architecturally, the frontend tracks true interactions via global listeners evaluating 'mousemove', 'keydown', and 'click', resetting a specialized non-re-rendering reference called idleTime.current down to exactly 0 upon trigger. Because intervals capture stale closures, LME leverages deep MutableRefObject caching so the socket emitter pushes actively synchronized numbers avoiding buggy duplicate interval leaks.</p>

<h2>5.3 Packet types</h2>
<p>Six major events orchestrate routing rules:</p>
<ul>
    <li>interval_update: Emitted globally at 5-second boundaries tracking passive progression.</li>
    <li>submit_answer: Sent instantly avoiding 5s delays capturing explicit answer boolean logics.</li>
    <li>session_complete: Forced closing packet capturing fully cumulative stats avoiding wipes.</li>
    <li>request_hint: Signal manually transmitted clicking Request Assistance buttons tracking Instructor SOS needs.</li>
    <li>state_change: Emitted directly upon internal CSS state calculation switches.</li>
    <li>hint_received: Explicitly emitted avoiding lag when async LLM generations land.</li>
</ul>

<h2>5.4 Lobby guard</h2>
<p>To prevent massive data poisoning against learners, the LME employs a precise Lobby Guard check mapping whenever module values equal 'Selecting...'. At the frontend level, classification generation evaluates strictly zero. On the backend, receiving selecting overrides avoids processing AI clustering loops and transmits simple update blobs notifying instructors indicating standard "In Lobby" variables dynamically protecting scoring integrity without closing sockets.</p>

<h1>6. Learner State Classification</h1>
<h2>6.1 Overview</h2>
<p>Runtime logic explicitly maps directly against discrete Boolean rules, pivoting off the historical Machine Learning backend. Although the Random Forest models remain cached in the repository, early analytical analysis observed critical mathematical mismatches. OULAD represented 30+ weeks of semester VLE clicks scaling into tens of thousands. LME environments evaluate 5-minute quiz sessions holding ~1,200 proxy-clicks max. To bridge functionality accurately, developers manually integrated Research-Supported specific interval triggers ensuring maximum confidence.</p>

<h2>6.2 Rule-based classification logic</h2>
<div class="code">IF is_correct_event:
    state = "Engaged"
ELSE IF attempt_count == 0 AND idle_time &lt; 20:
    state = "Engaged"
    // Immunity window for reading
ELSE IF idle_time &gt; 60:
    state = "Unengaged"
ELSE IF idle_time &gt;= 30 OR attempt_count &gt;= 3:
    state = "Struggling"
ELSE:
    state = "Engaged"</div>
<p>Rationale mapping dictates that unengaged values exceeding standard 120s "stuck/wandering" bounds should be cut down safely to roughly 60s for early detection. Meanwhile, the 3-attempt mark indicates an immediate explicit failure indicating a knowledge gap demanding scaffolding resolution.</p>

<h2>6.3 Struggle Index (SI) formula</h2>
<p>The explicit mathematical tracking generated inside ws.py routing logic reflects an independent normalized weighting score used to visualize intensity mapping locally inside Instructor Dashboard tracking:</p>
<div class="formula">SI = 0.4 × (idle_time / 120.0) + 0.4 × (attempt_count / 5.0) − 0.2 × (current_score / 1.0)</div>
<p>Weights evaluate exactly at 40% against idle periods divided by standard 120s thresholds, added to 40% evaluations on attempts scaled to absolute 5, heavily minimizing 20% subtractions evaluating core score competency parameters scaling natively 0.0-1.0.</p>

<h2>6.4 State debounce mechanism</h2>
<p>Since heartbeat systems generate exponential volume, the application deploys an active debounce algorithm tied directly to user client IDs utilizing last_state dictionaries and last_broadcast_time timestamps evaluated within a delta cutoff of precisely 3 seconds. An independent broadcast overrides this block strictly mapping whenever accurate completion packets push, eliminating dropping vital celebratory updates.</p>

<h2>6.5 Feedback messages</h2>
<p>The backend automatically embeds textual coaching payloads mapped explicitly based upon conditionals:</p>
<table>
    <tr><th>Triggers</th><th>Payload Message</th></tr>
    <tr><td>type == 'submit_answer' AND is_correct</td><td>"Excellent! That's correct, keep it up! 🎉"</td></tr>
    <tr><td>state == Struggling AND idle_time &gt;= 30</td><td>"You seem stuck. Take your time — or request a hint from your instructor."</td></tr>
    <tr><td>state == Struggling AND attempt_count &gt;= 3</td><td>"You've tried this a few times. Hint: try breaking the problem into smaller steps!"</td></tr>
    <tr><td>state == Unengaged</td><td>"You've been inactive for a while. Ready to continue? 👋"</td></tr>
    <tr><td>state == Engaged (heartbeat)</td><td>null (Silent mapping overriding popup UI)</td></tr>
</table>

<h1>7. WebSocket Architecture</h1>
<h2>7.1 ConnectionManager</h2>
<p>The ConnectionManager defines FastAPI memory pools defining class instance behaviors globally managing multiple lists: students dictionary wrapping client endpoints natively, an instructor array capturing monitoring peers, and latest_student_states holding exact fallback bootstrap caches resolving reconnection loads. Ghost disconnection safeguards ensure explicitly matching client WebSocket payload parameters via identity logic preventing false destruction events against active clients.</p>

<h2>7.2 Student WebSocket endpoint (/ws/{client_id})</h2>
<p>Processing routing is strictly sequenced: Connection initiates with forced JWT validations natively overriding unapproved clients immediately. First accepted loop maps directly to presence JSON variables. Secondary processing loops capture the active lobby logic ensuring skipping AI calculations internally. Valid operations then calculate exact native SI metrics triggering State Rules, generating Debounce string formats and finally dispatching native responses while mapping SQLite async blocks cleanly via TelemetryLog SQLAlchemy wrappers. The standard disconnection trigger triggers a "student_disconnected" feed payload cleaning the Dashboard immediately.</p>

<h2>7.3 Instructor WebSocket endpoint (/ws/instructor)</h2>
<p>When an instructor logs in, they bypass generic classification systems entirely utilizing a direct "instructor" client ID pipeline. Authenticated natively across HS256 tokens, the server iterates completely through latest_student_states emitting native payloads syncing exactly the live feed dynamically immediately. Standard loop processes accept zero metrics running infinite blocking logic keeping active states persisting.</p>

<h2>7.4 Dashboard update packet</h2>
<p>JSON packets bridging ws.py directly inside InstructorDashboard.jsx consist explicitly of: student_id, student_name, state classification variable, numerical si outputs, evaluated current_score mappings, raw idle_time counts, current_question, module texts, help_needed booleans, history objects matching arrays, and critical fully cumulative variables: totalMistakes, totalIdleTime, and totalHints validating exactly upon incoming merging logics resolving null defaults dynamically via caches.</p>

<h1>8. AI Hint System (ITS Engine)</h1>
<h2>8.1 Theoretical framework</h2>
<p>The AI modeling directly implements modern Intelligent Tutoring Systems (ITS) mapping against cognitive science. Utilizing Vygotsky's Zone of Proximal Development, the system calibrates exact scaffoldings based explicitly upon numerical scores. Integration of Productive Failure ensures students cannot demand clues unprompted ensuring attempt variables force authentic cognitive resistance initially. Generative instructions explicitly limit overreliance bounding the AI to never reveal answers blindly pushing student-dependent resolution directly.</p>

<h2>8.2 Three-layer ITS architecture</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Layer 1 — Domain Model:</strong> Defines exact question metadata representing pure numerical properties tied globally across static parameters mapping text, module and intrinsic difficulty string metrics.</li>
    <li><strong>Layer 2 — Student Model:</strong> Computes variables processing exact numerical values tracking cumulative hints, historical failures internally and historical LLM chat array mapping session-level chat records natively.</li>
    <li><strong>Layer 3 — Tutoring Model:</strong> Orchestrates mapping system strings directly inside GPT-4o-mini variables selecting intent models calculating explicitly based on scaffolding layers bounding LLM prompts safely.</li>
</ul>

<h2>8.3 HintRequest data model</h2>
<p>POST /hint receives a standardized HintRequest containing: question_text (string), module (string), attempt_count (int), current_score (float), difficulty (string), total_mistakes (int), answered_count (int), total_questions (int - invariably set to 10), hints_on_question (int), and an explicit array representing generic full-text conversation string arrays labelled history (list[HintMessage] dicts).</p>

<h2>8.4 Scaffolding level determination</h2>
<p>Level determinations force varying AI system parameter limits natively dependent directly on absolute current_score markers mapping Zone bounds:</p>
<table>
    <tr><th>Level</th><th>Threshold</th><th>Instruction Parameters</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Level 1 - Minimal</td><td>score &gt;= 0.80</td><td>Highly autonomous. Use open-ended probes only. Trust the student.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Level 2 - Low</td><td>score &gt;= 0.60</td><td>Mostly independent. Ask guiding questions. Encourage self-monitoring.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Level 3 - Moderate</td><td>score &gt;= 0.40</td><td>Needs regular support. Break down problems. Be explicit about the approach.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Level 4 - High</td><td>score &lt; 0.40</td><td>Requires substantial guidance. Give explicit step-by-step instruction.</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>8.5 Intent selection priority hierarchy</h2>
<p>Dynamic intent logic dictates LLM conversational positioning based purely upon escalation signals natively calculating (attempt_count + hints_on_question).</p>
<ul>
    <li>Priority 1: Reassure maps globally upon escalation &gt;= 6 OR attempt &gt;= 5 heavily requiring explicit direct emotional reassurance bounds natively capturing extreme frustration triggers.</li>
    <li>Priority 2: Teach integrates around escalation &gt;= 4 dynamically validating cognitive collapse mapping explicit formula level education outputs directly.</li>
    <li>Priority 3: Hint maps broadly upon escalation &gt;= 2 providing simple clue-based logic variables natively assisting specific blocks explicitly.</li>
    <li>Priority 4: Guide Self-Correction invokes when escalation == 1 capturing initial assistance requests targeting targeted errors explicitly via specific probing queries entirely.</li>
    <li>Default: Encourage runs exclusively dynamically outputting basic generic positive feedback natively.</li>
</ul>

<h2>8.6 Session memory</h2>
<p>Historically bound conversational limits dynamically trace hintHistory records globally. By mapping explicit role variables into session-level memory without wiping logic per question, GPT references exact string blocks verifying never to repeat phrases previously bound allowing true dynamic progression naturally capturing context universally over all 10 responses.</p>

<h2>8.7 GPT model configuration</h2>
<p>OpenAI is initialized with: gpt-4o-mini, max_tokens 150, temperature 0.7.</p>

<h2>8.8 Multiple hints per question</h2>
<p>The specific hints_on_question loop triggers specific label tracking UI modifications prompting 'Still confused? Get a simpler hint' avoiding generic loops inherently. Successive clicks drive escalation loops exponentially advancing threshold parameters mapping directly against exact GPT tracking variables explicitly prompting "MUST be MORE SPECIFIC than what you said before" explicitly overriding any duplicate outputs natively.</p>

<h2>8.9 Instructor AI broadcast</h2>
